{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Freshly initialized markets are immediately borrowable at a zero exchange rate","locations":["onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:993","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1028","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1050","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1139","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1331"],"claim":"`init()` sets the collateral/oracle fields but never seeds or validates `exchangeRate`. Until `updateExchangeRate()` succeeds at least once, the cached rate stays at its zero default, and every solvency check in `borrow()`, `removeCollateral()` and `cook()` trusts that zero value. With `_exchangeRate == 0`, `_isSolvent()` reduces the debt side of the comparison to zero, so any borrower with nonzero collateral is treated as solvent regardless of debt size.","impact":"The first borrower in a newly created market can post dust collateral and drain all MIM available in the Cauldron before anyone performs a successful oracle update. If the configured oracle keeps returning `updated == false` or otherwise never seeds a nonzero cached rate, the market can remain permanently unliquidatable while bad debt accumulates.","paths":["Deploy or clone a new Cauldron -> fund it with MIM -> attacker adds minimal collateral -> attacker calls `borrow()` before any successful `updateExchangeRate()` -> solvency check passes at `exchangeRate == 0` -> attacker drains available MIM","Deploy a market with an oracle that never returns an updated rate -> cached `exchangeRate` remains zero -> attacker repeatedly borrows against tiny collateral and cannot be liquidated using the same zero-rate solvency logic"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Solvency-critical actions trust arbitrarily stale cached oracle prices","locations":["onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1057","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1117","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1139","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1297","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1331","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1346"],"claim":"The protocol stores a single cached `exchangeRate` and never enforces freshness for solvency-sensitive actions. `borrow()` and `removeCollateral()` only call `accrue()` before checking solvency, and `cook()` reuses the cached storage value unless the caller explicitly inserts `ACTION_UPDATE_EXCHANGE_RATE`. Even liquidation accepts stale data by calling `updateExchangeRate()` and falling back to the previous cached rate whenever `oracle.get()` returns `updated == false`.","impact":"After adverse price moves, borrowers can race keepers and borrow too much or withdraw too much collateral against a stale favorable rate, leaving the market undercollateralized once a fresh price arrives. In the opposite direction, if the cached rate is stale-high and the oracle update fails, healthy users can be liquidated against an obsolete punitive price.","paths":["Collateral price falls -> cached rate is still low -> borrower calls `borrow()` or `removeCollateral()` without refreshing the oracle -> stale solvency check passes -> protocol inherits bad debt when the exchange rate is eventually refreshed","Collateral price recovers -> cached rate remains high -> `oracle.get()` fails during `liquidate()` so the function reuses the stale cached rate -> healthy users are liquidated at an outdated price"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"`cook()` max-rate protection is inverted and only passes above the caller's ceiling","locations":["onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1295","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1298"],"claim":"`ACTION_UPDATE_EXCHANGE_RATE` decodes `(must_update, minRate, maxRate)` but enforces `(maxRate == 0 || rate > maxRate)` instead of the intended upper-bound check `rate <= maxRate`. As written, any nonzero `maxRate` makes the action revert for acceptable prices and succeed only once the oracle price is already worse than the caller's declared ceiling.","impact":"Users and integrations cannot rely on `cook()` for oracle slippage protection. Atomic sequences that are supposed to abort when the oracle exceeds a tolerated bound can instead execute only at explicitly disallowed prices, undermining protected borrow and collateral-withdraw workflows.","paths":["Integrator builds a `cook()` bundle with `ACTION_UPDATE_EXCHANGE_RATE(maxRate = X)` before `ACTION_BORROW` or `ACTION_REMOVE_COLLATERAL`","Oracle rate moves above `X` -> the inverted predicate still passes -> the protected action executes under a price the caller explicitly tried to forbid"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Permissionless `cook()` calls can sweep stray ETH and directly transferred tokens from the Cauldron","locations":["onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:993","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1217","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1233","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1252","onchain_auto/0xbb02a884621fb8f5bfd263a67f58b65df5b090f3/Contract.sol:1269"],"claim":"The Cauldron accepts ETH in payable entry points (`init()` and `cook()`), and `cook()` forwards each `values[i]` into `_bentoDeposit()` or `_call()` from the contract's own ETH balance without ever enforcing that the total forwarded ETH is bounded by the caller's `msg.value`. Any ETH already sitting on the Cauldron can therefore be spent by a later caller. Separately, `ACTION_CALL` lets anyone execute arbitrary external calls from the Cauldron context, so ERC20 tokens that were mistakenly transferred directly to the Cauldron can be swept with a token `transfer()` call.","impact":"Any ETH stranded on the Cauldron—such as deployment ETH sent to payable `init()`, overpaid `cook()` value, or force-sent ETH—can be stolen by the next arbitrary caller. Tokens accidentally sent directly to the Cauldron instead of BentoBox can likewise be permissionlessly transferred out to an attacker.","paths":["ETH is left on the Cauldron via payable `init()`, an overfunded `cook()` call, or forced transfer -> attacker calls `cook()` with `ACTION_CALL` (or another value-consuming action) and a nonzero `values[i]` -> the contract spends its preexisting ETH balance for the attacker","A victim transfers an ERC20 directly to the Cauldron address -> attacker calls `cook()` with `ACTION_CALL` targeting that token's `transfer(attacker, amount)` -> the token balance held by the Cauldron is swept"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Missing access control on init function allows setting malicious oracle","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`init()` is the intended clone initializer invoked during `BentoBox.deploy`; no concrete path was shown to hijack already deployed funded markets, and initializing the master contract itself does not compromise existing clones."},{"title":"Reentrancy vulnerability in liquidate function via arbitrary swapper","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The swapper callback occurs before the final MIM repayment transfer, and any failure to repay reverts the entire liquidation; no concrete reentrant path to steal collateral or corrupt accounting was validated."},{"title":"No slippage protection in liquidation swap","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Open liquidation intentionally lets the caller choose `to` and `swapper`; the liquidator bears that execution risk, so this is not a protocol vulnerability."},{"title":"Oracle price not validated for reasonableness","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a generic oracle-trust observation rather than a distinct code flaw; the concrete reportable oracle issues here are the stale/zero cached-rate behaviors already captured separately."},{"title":"Open liquidation allows front-running and MEV extraction","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Permissionless liquidation and MEV competition are expected market mechanics, not a code-level vulnerability."},{"title":"Potential integer overflow in accrue interest calculation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The arithmetic is checked, and the described overflow requires extreme/unrealistic values or time horizons, making it non-practical as a protocol risk."},{"title":"Missing event for critical reduceSupply function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Informational only; it does not create realistic protocol-level harm."},{"title":"No access control on setFeeTo function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`setFeeTo()` is protected by `onlyOwner`; setting a poor recipient is an authorized governance choice, not missing access control."}]}
